com.calendarfx.model

Class Calendar

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.calendarfx.model.Calendar
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    EventTarget

    public class Calendar
extends Object
implements EventTarget
    A calendar is responsible for storing calendar entries. It provides methods for adding, removing, and querying entries. A calendar also defines a visual style / color theme that will be used throughout the UI controls. Calendars fire events whenever entries are added or removed. Calendars are grouped together inside a CalendarSource. These calendar sources are then added to DateControl.getCalendarSources().

    Example

         
     // create the calendar and listen to all changes
     Calendar calendar = new Calendar("Home");
     calendar.addEventHandler(CalendarEvent.ANY, evt -> handleEvent(evt));

     // create the calendar source and attach the calendar
     CalendarSource source = new CalendarSource("Online Calendars");
     source.getCalendars().add(calendar);

     // attach the source to the date control / calendar view.
     CalendarView view = new CalendarView();
     view.getCalendarSources().add(source);

    • Property Detail

      • lookAheadDuration

        public final ObjectProperty<Duration> lookAheadDurationProperty
        Stores a time duration used for the entry search functionality of this calendar. The look ahead and the look back durations limit the search to the time interval [now - lookBackDuration, now + lookAheadDuration]. The default value of this property is 730 days (2 years).
        See Also:
        getLookAheadDuration(), setLookAheadDuration(Duration)

      • startBatchUpdates

        public final void startBatchUpdates()
        Tells the calendar that the application will perform a large number of changes. While batch updates in progress the calendar will stop to fire events. To finish this mode the application has to call stopBatchUpdates().

      • stopBatchUpdates

        public final void stopBatchUpdates()
        Tells the calendar that the application is done making big changes. Invoking this method will trigger a calendar event of type CalendarEvent.CALENDAR_CHANGED which will then force an update of the views.
